Hyperparam tuning name: learning_rate. The solution wraps the
training‐validation procedure into a loop over four initial learning rates,
re‐initializes the model and optimizer for each rate, and records per‐epoch
losses and entropy ratios under a nested key in
`experiment_data['learning_rate']`. After training, it also generates a sample
prediction, stores both predictions and ground truth, and saves all results via
`np.save`. Each learning‐rate run additionally produces its own generation plot
in the `working` directory.

We propose to enhance the compressive memory by computing per‐head attention
entropies and selecting tokens based on their maximum per‐head novelty,
preserving those with the highest surprise across any head. We load three
HuggingFace datasets (PG19, Scientific Papers ArXiv, and WikiText‐2) and
subsample them for quick prototyping; each text is mapped to a byte‐level token
stream by character ordinals mod 256. Our ImprovedMemoryTransformerLayer
computes per‐head entropies, merges them into a scalar per‐token score, and
retains the top‐k highest‐entropy tokens. We train and validate for two epochs
per dataset, tracking validation loss and the novel Entropy‐Weighted Memory
Efficiency (sum of retained token entropies divided by slots used), as well as
overall Memory Retention Ratio. All metrics and losses are stored in a nested
`experiment_data` dict and saved as a numpy file; validation loss is printed
each epoch. This pipeline runs on GPU if available and completes in under an
hour on the subsampled splits, ready for scaling to full datasets.

We extend our previous MemoryTransformer architecture by replacing fixed-size
compression with a dynamic entropy threshold: tokens whose self-attention
entropy exceeds the running mean entropy (scaled by a factor) are retained while
others are discarded. This adaptive budget allows the model to flexibly prune
low-novelty slots and preserve salient context. We integrate this layer into a
Transformer-XL style LM and benchmark on three HuggingFace language-modeling
datasets: PG19, arXiv (scientific_papers), and Wikitext-103. Each corpus is
tokenized with the GPT-2 tokenizer, chunked into sliding-window blocks, and fed
via small batches with chunked forward passes to trigger dynamic compression. We
log validation loss (perplexity proxy) each epoch, compute an Entropy-Weighted
Memory Efficiency metric (mean entropy preserved per slot), and save all losses
and metrics for later analysis. This setup will reveal whether entropy-
thresholding yields better long-range retention and efficiency across diverse
long-text sources.

We extend the previous synthetic benchmark to three real long‐context
HuggingFace corpora (PG19, ArXiv abstracts, WikiText-2) using streaming and
on‐the‐fly tokenization with GPT2Tokenizer. Each dataset is sampled to a small
curated split of 20 sequences of 128 tokens for fast prototyping, and split
equally into train and validation sets. We maintain the Entropy‐Aware Adaptive
Compressive Memory module, but augment it to compute the Entropy‐Weighted Memory
Efficiency (EWME) metric—i.e. average self‐attention entropy per retained
slot—at each forward pass. We train a lightweight MemoryTransformerXL model for
2 epochs per dataset, tracking train/val losses and EWME per epoch. For
qualitative analysis, we generate one autoregressive sample per validation set
and plot predicted vs. ground‐truth tokens, saving figures under working_dir
with unique names. All tensors, models, and computations are properly moved to
GPU when available. Finally, we serialize the full experiment_data structure
(including metrics, predictions, and ground truth) as a NumPy file. This script
runs end‐to‐end without external entry points and completes within an hour on
modest hardware.

We refactor the MemoryTransformerLayer to maintain separate memory and entropy
buffers for each element in the batch by iterating over the batch dimension,
calling MultiheadAttention per‐sample, and pruning each memory independently.
We also switch to HuggingFace’s streaming API to avoid long download times and
limit to a small subset of examples.  The training and validation loops now
collect per‐epoch entropy‐efficiency metrics, losses, and record predictions and
ground truth sequences for the validation set, and we save everything into
`experiment_data.npy` at the end.

We switch to streaming dataset loading and only iterate until `max_texts`
examples to avoid slicing and downloading the full splits, eliminating the
timeout. We remove `.select` and percent-based splits and break after collecting
50 texts per dataset. Additionally, we set `batch_size=1` to keep the memory
buffer aligned with the single-sample memory‐tracking logic. The rest of the
model definitions, training loop, and metric logging remain unchanged.

We can avoid the long download and mapping delays by using the datasets
library’s streaming mode to fetch only a small subset of each dataset (e.g., 200
training and 100 validation examples). We then manually encode these samples,
build small TensorDatasets, and use DataLoader as before. This streaming
approach prevents full dataset downloads and heavy mapping operations, ensuring
the script completes quickly while still testing on three HuggingFace
collections.

We can fix the tokenizer error by removing the unsupported `add_special_tokens`
flag from `from_pretrained()` and instead pass it to the actual encoding calls.
This change preserves existing behavior while eliminating the attribute
conflict. All other training and memory‐compression logic remains unchanged so
the script runs end‐to‐end.

We extend EA-ACM across three Hugging Face corpora—PG19, Wikitext-2, and Penn
Treebank—by tokenizing with GPT2TokenizerFast and generating fixed-length (64
token) segments for causal LM. Each dataset is subsampled to 200 train and 50
validation examples, and turned into PyTorch DataLoaders. We reuse the
MemoryTransformerLayer to compute per-token attention entropy and adaptively
compress the KV buffer, returning entropies for metric tracking. A light
TransformerXLModel (embed_dim=128, 4 heads) is trained for one epoch on each
dataset, with chunking (32 tokens) to simulate long-context processing. At every
epoch we compute and print the validation loss and the average Entropy-Weighted
Memory Efficiency (total retained entropy divided by memory slots). After
training on each corpus, we generate sample continuations from the first
validation sequence, plot predicted vs. ground truth token IDs, and save the
figures. All losses, metrics, predictions, and ground truths are stored in an
`experiment_data` dict keyed by dataset, then saved as a NumPy file in the
working directory.

We introduce a learned gating network conditioned on both per‐token entropy and
token embeddings to adaptively score each memory slot before compression. This
Gated Entropy‐Aware Memory (GEAM) module replaces fixed selection by computing a
retention score via a small MLP whose input is the embedding and entropy of each
token. At each step when memory exceeds the budget, we rank tokens by the
product of entropy and the learned gate sigmoid, keeping the top slots. We
integrate this GEAM layer into a Transformer‐XL backbone and evaluate on three
HuggingFace streaming datasets: PG19, scientific_papers/arxiv, and
wikitext‐2‐raw. We track validation loss, Memory Retention Ratio, and
Entropy‐Weighted Memory Efficiency at every epoch and save all metrics. This
learned gating can adapt to different data distributions, potentially preserving
more task‐relevant context than pure entropy ranking. We use small streaming
subsets for fast iteration and ensure GPU usage throughout. Results will
highlight whether the gated model outperforms the original entropy‐only
compressor in both perplexity and memory efficiency. All code runs end‐to‐end
without needing special entry points and stores experimental data in
“working/experiment_data.npy”.

We add a pad token to GPT2 so that padding works, by assigning
`tokenizer.pad_token = tokenizer.eos_token`. We then scale up the run by raising
the number of epochs to 3 and using more data (1000 train, 200 val). We also
reorganize `experiment_data` to separate losses and entropy‐weighted memory
efficiency under “metrics” for train/val, and print both validation loss and
“entropy_weighted_memory_efficiency” each epoch. All models and tensors are
moved to `device`, and results (metrics, losses, preds, and GT) are saved to
`./working/experiment_data.npy`.

import os

working_dir = os.path.join(os.getcwd(), "working")
os.makedirs(working_dir, exist_ok=True)

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim
import numpy as np
from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
print(f"Using device: {device}")


# Synthetic dataset
class RandomSeqDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, num_seqs, total_len, vocab_size):
        self.data = torch.randint(
            1, vocab_size, (num_seqs, total_len), dtype=torch.long
        )

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        seq = self.data[idx]
        return {"input": seq[:-1], "target": seq[1:]}


vocab_size = 50
seq_total = 51  # input 50, target 50
train_ds = RandomSeqDataset(200, seq_total, vocab_size)
val_ds = RandomSeqDataset(50, seq_total, vocab_size)
train_loader = DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=1, shuffle=True)
val_loader = DataLoader(val_ds, batch_size=1)


# Model with entropy‐aware memory
class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size = mem_size

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        if mem_x is None:
            k = v = x
        else:
            k = torch.cat([mem_x.unsqueeze(0), x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        aw = attn_w.mean(dim=1)[0]  # (tgt_len, src_len)
        eps = 1e-10
        ent = -(aw * (aw + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1).detach()  # (tgt_len,)
        x_det = x.detach()[0]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent], dim=0)
        total_ent = mem_ent_new.sum().item() + eps
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size:
            idx = torch.topk(mem_ent_new, self.mem_size).indices
            kept_ent = mem_ent_new[idx].sum().item()
            ratio = kept_ent / total_ent
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
        else:
            ratio = 1.0
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio


class TransformerXLModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, vocab_size, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.embed = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim)
        self.mem_layer = MemoryTransformerLayer(embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size)
        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        emb = self.embed(x)
        out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio = self.mem_layer(emb, mem_x, mem_ent)
        logits = self.out(out)
        return logits, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio


# Hyperparameter tuning over learning rates
learning_rates = [1e-4, 5e-4, 1e-3, 5e-3]
experiment_data = {"learning_rate": {}}

num_epochs = 3
chunk_size = 10

for lr in learning_rates:
    key = f"{lr}"
    print(f"\n=== Tuning learning rate: {key} ===")
    # initialize model, optimizer, criterion
    model = TransformerXLModel(vocab_size, embed_dim=64, num_heads=2, mem_size=20).to(
        device
    )
    optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=lr)
    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    # prepare storage
    exp = {
        "metrics": {"train": [], "val": []},
        "losses": {"train": [], "val": []},
        "predictions": [],
        "ground_truth": [],
    }
    # training loop
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        train_loss, train_ratios = 0.0, []
        for batch in train_loader:
            batch = {k: v.to(device) for k, v in batch.items()}
            inp, tgt = batch["input"], batch["target"]
            mem_x = mem_ent = None
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss_accum = 0.0
            for i in range(0, inp.size(1), chunk_size):
                ic = inp[:, i : i + chunk_size]
                tc = tgt[:, i : i + chunk_size]
                logits, mem_x, mem_ent, ratio = model(ic, mem_x, mem_ent)
                loss = criterion(logits.reshape(-1, vocab_size), tc.reshape(-1))
                loss_accum += loss
                train_ratios.append(ratio)
            loss_accum.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            train_loss += loss_accum.item() / (inp.size(1) / chunk_size)
        avg_train_loss = train_loss / len(train_loader)
        avg_train_ratio = sum(train_ratios) / len(train_ratios)
        exp["losses"]["train"].append(avg_train_loss)
        exp["metrics"]["train"].append(avg_train_ratio)
        # validation loop
        model.eval()
        val_loss, val_ratios = 0.0, []
        with torch.no_grad():
            for batch in val_loader:
                batch = {k: v.to(device) for k, v in batch.items()}
                inp, tgt = batch["input"], batch["target"]
                mem_x = mem_ent = None
                loss_acc = 0.0
                for i in range(0, inp.size(1), chunk_size):
                    ic = inp[:, i : i + chunk_size]
                    tc = tgt[:, i : i + chunk_size]
                    logits, mem_x, mem_ent, ratio = model(ic, mem_x, mem_ent)
                    loss_acc += criterion(
                        logits.reshape(-1, vocab_size), tc.reshape(-1)
                    )
                    val_ratios.append(ratio)
                val_loss += loss_acc.item() / (inp.size(1) / chunk_size)
        avg_val_loss = val_loss / len(val_loader)
        avg_val_ratio = sum(val_ratios) / len(val_ratios)
        exp["losses"]["val"].append(avg_val_loss)
        exp["metrics"]["val"].append(avg_val_ratio)
        print(f"LR {key} Epoch {epoch} val_loss={avg_val_loss:.4f}")
    # generation on first val sequence
    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        sample = val_ds[0]["input"].unsqueeze(0).to(device)
        target = val_ds[0]["target"].tolist()
        mem_x = mem_ent = None
        preds = []
        for t in range(sample.size(1)):
            inp_t = sample[:, t].unsqueeze(1)
            logits, mem_x, mem_ent, _ = model(inp_t, mem_x, mem_ent)
            p = torch.softmax(logits.squeeze(0).squeeze(0), dim=-1)
            preds.append(int(p.argmax().item()))
        exp["predictions"] = preds
        exp["ground_truth"] = target
    # plot
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(range(len(preds)), preds, label="predicted")
    plt.plot(range(len(target)), target, label="ground_truth")
    plt.legend()
    plt.savefig(os.path.join(working_dir, f"synthetic_generation_{key}.png"))
    plt.close()
    # store
    experiment_data["learning_rate"][key] = {"synthetic": exp}

# save everything
np.save(os.path.join(working_dir, "experiment_data.npy"), experiment_data)

num_heads = 2
mem_size = 50
chunk_size = 32

lr = 1e-3


# Define improved memory layer
class ImprovedMemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size = mem_size

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        B, T, E = x.size()
        if mem_x is None:
            k = v = x
        else:
            mem = mem_x.unsqueeze(0).expand(B, -1, -1)
            k = torch.cat([mem, x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        # per-head entropy
        eps = 1e-10
        ent_h = -(attn_w * (attn_w + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1)  # B, heads, T
        ent_tok = ent_h[0].max(dim=0)[0]  # take max across heads, shape T
        x_det = x.detach()[0]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent_tok
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent_tok], dim=0)
        # compress if needed
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size:
            total_ent = mem_ent_new.sum().item() + eps
            _, idx = torch.topk(mem_ent_new, self.mem_size)
            kept_ent = mem_ent_new[idx].sum().item()
            ratio = kept_ent / total_ent
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
        else:
            ratio = 1.0
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio


class ImprovedTransformerXLModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, vocab_size, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.embed = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim)
        self.mem_layer = ImprovedMemoryTransformerLayer(embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size)
        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        emb = self.embed(x)
        out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio = self.mem_layer(emb, mem_x, mem_ent)
        logits = self.out(out)
        return logits, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio


# Prepare experiment_data container

# Datasets to use
configs = [
    ("pg19", None),
    ("scientific_papers", "arxiv"),
    ("wikitext", "wikitext-2-raw-v1"),
]

    txt = example.get("text") or example.get("abstract", "")
    txt = txt[: max_len + 1]
    ids = [ord(c) % vocab_size for c in txt]
    if len(ids) < max_len + 1:

    return {"input": ids[:-1], "target": ids[1:]}

    )
    optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=lr)

import random

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim
from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader
import numpy as np
from datasets import load_dataset
from transformers import AutoTokenizer

device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
print(f"Using device: {device}")


# Dynamic entropy‐thresholded memory layer
class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size_base = mem_size_base
        self.threshold_factor = threshold_factor

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        # x: [batch, seq, dim]
        if mem_x is None:
            k, v = x, x
        else:
            k = torch.cat([mem_x.unsqueeze(0), x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(

        ent_eff = mem_ent_new.sum().item() / mem_ent_new.size(0)
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ent_eff

        if len(sequences) >= 2 * sample_size:

class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size = mem_size

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        if mem_x is None:
            k = v = x
        else:
            k = torch.cat([mem_x.unsqueeze(0), x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        aw = attn_w.mean(dim=1)[0]
        eps = 1e-10
        ent = -(aw * (aw + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1).detach()
        x_det = x.detach()[0]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent], dim=0)
        total_ent = mem_ent_new.sum().item() + eps
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size:
            idx = torch.topk(mem_ent_new, self.mem_size).indices
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
        mem_eff = mem_ent_new.sum().item() / mem_ent_new.size(0)
        ratio = mem_ent_new.sum().item() / total_ent
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio, mem_eff

        )

class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):

        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)

            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size_base = mem_size_base
        self.threshold_factor = threshold_factor

    def forward(self, x, mems_x, mems_ent):
        # x: [batch, seq, dim]
        batch, seq, dim = x.size()
        out_list, new_mems_x, new_mems_ent, effs = [], [], [], []
        eps = 1e-8
        for b in range(batch):
            x_b = x[b : b + 1]  # [1, seq, dim]
            mem_b = None if mems_x is None else mems_x[b]
            ent_b_prev = None if mems_ent is None else mems_ent[b]
            if mem_b is None:
                k = v = x_b
            else:
                k = torch.cat([mem_b.unsqueeze(0), x_b], dim=1)
                v = k
            attn_out_b, attn_w_b = self.attn(
                x_b, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
            )
            x2_b = self.norm1(x_b + attn_out_b)
            out_b = self.norm2(x2_b + self.ff(x2_b))
            # compute per-token entropy
            # attn_w_b: [1, num_heads, seq, src]
            aw = attn_w_b[0].mean(dim=0)  # [seq, src]
            ent_cur = -(aw * (aw + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1).detach()  # [seq]
            # new memory entries: detach input embeddings
            mem_new = x_b.squeeze(0).detach()  # [seq, dim]
            if mem_b is None:
                mx = mem_new
                me = ent_cur
            else:
                mx = torch.cat([mem_b, mem_new], dim=0)
                me = torch.cat([ent_b_prev, ent_cur], dim=0)
            # thresholded pruning
            if mx.size(0) > self.mem_size_base:
                thresh = me.mean() * self.threshold_factor
                idx = (me >= thresh).nonzero().squeeze(1)
                if idx.numel() > self.mem_size_base:
                    idx = torch.topk(me, self.mem_size_base).indices
                mx = mx[idx]
                me = me[idx]
            ent_eff = me.sum().item() / me.numel()
            out_list.append(out_b)
            new_mems_x.append(mx)
            new_mems_ent.append(me)
            effs.append(ent_eff)
        out = torch.cat(out_list, dim=0)  # [batch, seq, dim]
        return out, new_mems_x, new_mems_ent, sum(effs) / len(effs)

# Dynamic entropy‐thresholded memory layer
class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size_base = mem_size_base
        self.threshold_factor = threshold_factor

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        # x: [batch=1, seq, dim]
        if mem_x is None:
            k, v = x, x
        else:
            k = torch.cat([mem_x.unsqueeze(0), x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        # compute entropy for the single batch element
        aw = attn_w.mean(dim=1)[0]  # [seq, src]
        eps = 1e-8
        ent = -(aw * (aw + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1).detach()  # [seq]
        x_det = x.detach()[0]  # [seq, dim]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent], dim=0)
        # thresholded pruning
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size_base:
            thresh = mem_ent_new.mean() * self.threshold_factor
            idx = (mem_ent_new >= thresh).nonzero().squeeze(1)
            if idx.numel() > self.mem_size_base:
                idx = torch.topk(mem_ent_new, self.mem_size_base).indices
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
        ent_eff = mem_ent_new.sum().item() / mem_ent_new.size(0)
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ent_eff


class TransformerXLModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(
        self, vocab_size, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor
    ):
        super().__init__()
        self.embed = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim)
        self.mem_layer = MemoryTransformerLayer(
            embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor
        )
        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        emb = self.embed(x)
        out, mx, me, eff = self.mem_layer(emb, mem_x, mem_ent)
        logits = self.out(out)
        return logits, mx, me, eff

class GatedMemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size):
        super().__init__()

        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size = mem_size
        self.gate = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim + 1, hid_dim), nn.ReLU(), nn.Linear(hid_dim, 1)
        )

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        B, T, E = x.size()
        if mem_x is None:
            k = v = x
        else:
            mem = mem_x.unsqueeze(0).expand(B, -1, -1)
            k = torch.cat([mem, x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        eps = 1e-10
        ent_h = -(attn_w * (attn_w + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1)  # B, heads, T
        ent_tok = ent_h[0].max(dim=0)[0]  # T
        x_det = x.detach()[0]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent_tok
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent_tok], dim=0)
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size:
            feats = torch.cat([mem_x_new, mem_ent_new.unsqueeze(1)], dim=1)
            scores = self.gate(feats).squeeze(-1)
            ret_scores = mem_ent_new * torch.sigmoid(scores)
            _, idx = torch.topk(ret_scores, self.mem_size)
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
            ratio = mem_ent_new.sum().item() / (mem_ent_new.sum().item() + eps)
        else:
            ratio = 1.0
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio

        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

        emb = self.embed(x)
        out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio = self.mem_layer(emb, mem_x, mem_ent)
        logits = self.out(out)
        return logits, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio

class MemoryTransformerLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(embed_dim, 4 * embed_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size_base = mem_size_base
        self.threshold_factor = threshold_factor

    def forward(self, x, mems_x, mems_ent):
        batch, seq, dim = x.size()
        out_list, new_mems_x, new_mems_ent, effs = [], [], [], []
        eps = 1e-8
        for b in range(batch):
            x_b = x[b : b + 1]
            mem_b = None if mems_x is None else mems_x[b]
            ent_b_prev = None if mems_ent is None else mems_ent[b]
            if mem_b is None:
                k = v = x_b
            else:
                k = torch.cat([mem_b.unsqueeze(0), x_b], dim=1)
                v = k
            attn_out_b, attn_w_b = self.attn(
                x_b, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
            )
            x2_b = self.norm1(x_b + attn_out_b)
            out_b = self.norm2(x2_b + self.ff(x2_b))
            aw = attn_w_b[0].mean(dim=0)
            ent_cur = -(aw * (aw + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1).detach()
            mem_new = x_b.squeeze(0).detach()
            if mem_b is None:
                mx, me = mem_new, ent_cur
            else:
                mx = torch.cat([mem_b, mem_new], dim=0)
                me = torch.cat([ent_b_prev, ent_cur], dim=0)
            if mx.size(0) > self.mem_size_base:
                thresh = me.mean() * self.threshold_factor
                idx = (me >= thresh).nonzero().squeeze(1)
                if idx.numel() > self.mem_size_base:
                    idx = torch.topk(me, self.mem_size_base).indices
                mx, me = mx[idx], me[idx]
            ent_eff = me.sum().item() / me.numel()
            out_list.append(out_b)
            new_mems_x.append(mx)
            new_mems_ent.append(me)
            effs.append(ent_eff)
        out = torch.cat(out_list, dim=0)
        return out, new_mems_x, new_mems_ent, sum(effs) / len(effs)


class TransformerXLModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(
        self, vocab_size, embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor
    ):
        super().__init__()
        self.embed = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim)
        self.mem_layer = MemoryTransformerLayer(
            embed_dim, num_heads, mem_size_base, threshold_factor
        )
        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x, mems_x, mems_ent):
        emb = self.embed(x)
        out_mem, mx, me, eff = self.mem_layer(emb, mems_x, mems_ent)
        logits = self.out(out_mem)
        return logits, mx, me, eff

        super().__init__()

        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(

            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(4 * embed_dim, embed_dim),
        )
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
        self.mem_size = mem_size

    def forward(self, x, mem_x, mem_ent):
        B, T, E = x.size()
        if mem_x is None:
            k = v = x
        else:
            mem = mem_x.unsqueeze(0).expand(B, -1, -1)
            k = torch.cat([mem, x], dim=1)
            v = k
        attn_out, attn_w = self.attn(
            x, k, v, need_weights=True, average_attn_weights=False
        )
        x2 = self.norm1(x + attn_out)
        out = self.norm2(x2 + self.ff(x2))
        eps = 1e-10
        ent_h = -(attn_w * (attn_w + eps).log()).sum(dim=-1)  # B, heads, T
        ent_tok = ent_h[0].max(dim=0)[0]  # take max across heads, shape T
        x_det = x.detach()[0]
        if mem_x is None:
            mem_x_new = x_det
            mem_ent_new = ent_tok
        else:
            mem_x_new = torch.cat([mem_x, x_det], dim=0)
            mem_ent_new = torch.cat([mem_ent, ent_tok], dim=0)
        if mem_x_new.size(0) > self.mem_size:
            total_ent = mem_ent_new.sum().item() + eps
            _, idx = torch.topk(mem_ent_new, self.mem_size)
            kept_ent = mem_ent_new[idx].sum().item()
            ratio = kept_ent / total_ent
            mem_x_new = mem_x_new[idx]
            mem_ent_new = mem_ent_new[idx]
        else:
            ratio = 1.0
        return out, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio

        self.out = nn.Linear(embed_dim, vocab_size)

        emb = self.embed(x)

        logits = self.out(out)
        return logits, mem_x_new, mem_ent_new, ratio

analysis:
The training script never completed within the 1-hour time limit because it
attempted to download and prepare full datasets (pg19, scientific_papers/arxiv,
and wikitext-2) before subsampling. The huge volume of data (especially
scientific_papers) caused excessively long download times and ultimately a
TimeoutError. Proposed fix: load only the required subset via streaming (e.g.,
`load_dataset(..., streaming=True, split='train[:200]')`), or pre-download/cache
smaller splits, so that the code does not fetch the entire dataset before
slicing.

The script hung and timed out when calling load_dataset('pg19',
split='train[:1%]') because load_dataset still tries to download and prepare the
entire PG19 dataset before yielding even 1% of data. This caused the execution
to exceed the time limit. Proposed fix: use the streaming mode
(load_dataset(..., split='train[:1%]', streaming=True)) to avoid downloading the
full dataset, or pre-download/cache the dataset locally, or choose a smaller
dataset/config for rapid development.

The script crashes when loading the GPT2 tokenizer due to passing
add_special_tokens to from_pretrained, which conflicts with an existing
tokenizer method. To fix this, remove add_special_tokens from the
from_pretrained call and instead set it when encoding inputs (e.g.,
tokenizer(txt, add_special_tokens=False)), or load the tokenizer normally and
control special tokens at tokenization time.

The training script crashed at line 202 with a RuntimeError: view size is not
compatible with input tensor's size and stride. This is due to using .view() on
a non-contiguous tensor resulting from chunked logits; .reshape() or calling
.contiguous().view() should be used instead. Additionally, the Hugging Face
tokenizer warns about input sequences exceeding its max_length (1024) because
texts are tokenized in full. To avoid this, specify truncation=True and
max_length (e.g., block_size+1) when tokenizing or pre-chunk the text before
tokenization.

The data loader crashes when preparing the 'scientific_papers' dataset: in
streaming mode the examples (x) appear as raw strings rather than dicts, so
x['article']['abstract'] raises a TypeError. Proposed fix: disable streaming
(remove streaming=True) so that examples are full dicts, or adjust the loader to
treat x as a string (e.g. use x directly or load with the correct keys).
Additionally, enable truncation in the tokenizer call to avoid extremely long
token sequences warnings.

The script fails during dataset tokenization with GPT2Tokenizer because it has
no pad_token defined, yet padding is requested (padding='max_length'). To fix
this, after loading the tokenizer add a pad token—e.g.:  ``` tokenizer =
GPT2TokenizerFast.from_pretrained("gpt2") tokenizer.pad_token =
tokenizer.eos_token  # or tokenizer.add_special_tokens({'pad_token':'[PAD]'})
```  This ensures padding operations succeed without error.

The data-loading function `get_dataloaders` unconditionally uses the key
`'text'` inside `tok_fn`, but the Penn Treebank dataset (`ptb_text_only`)
defines its sentences under a different column name (e.g. `'sentence'`). This
mismatch triggers a KeyError and aborts execution when processing the second
dataset. To fix this, modify `tok_fn` to dynamically select the correct text
column—either by reading from `ds_train.column_names[0]`, by looking up a
mapping of dataset names to their text column, or by falling back through
possible keys (e.g. `ex.get('text', ex.get('sentence'))`)—so that each dataset
is tokenized using its actual text field.

plot_analyses.analysis: Overlay of predicted vs ground truth values across 50 time steps shows large misalignments and erratic behavior. The model occasionally captures peaks in the ground truth (e.g., around steps 1–5 and 30–35) but frequently misses significant spikes or predicts flat regions when the truth is high. Noise in the predictions suggests underfitting or insufficient context retention by the baseline compressive memory. High-amplitude fluctuations are not consistently tracked, indicating the need for stronger signal preservation or longer training.

Memory retention ratios measured on the synthetic dataset across three epochs reveal a strong dependence on learning rate. Low learning rates (1e-4, 5e-4) and moderate rate (1e-3) yield nearly constant retention around 0.82 on both train and validation, indicating minimal adaptation of the compressive memory. A higher rate (5e-3) drives retention upward from ~0.84 to ~0.856 on validation, showing the strongest improvement in stored information. However, stability in retention is flat for other rates, suggesting that only the largest rate effectively allows the entropy-based controller to update memory targets within three epochs.

Overlay of predicted vs ground truth values over 50 steps for a second synthetic run again reveals large discrepancies. Although some local alignment occurs in early segments (steps ~0–6), the model drifts for mid- and long-range tokens, failing to track sudden increases beyond ~40 or sudden drops below ~10. Variability remains uncontrolled, pointing to inconsistency across random seeds or training settings. A tuning of batch size or gradient noise scale may help stabilize these predictions.

Loss curves on the synthetic dataset across three epochs show that the learning rate of 1e-3 achieves the steepest training loss drop (from ~3.95 to ~3.67) and corresponding validation decrease (from ~3.90 to ~3.80). A lower rate (5e-4) also reduces loss but more slowly, while the smallest rate (1e-4) barely moves and higher rate (5e-3) yields flat or plateaued validation loss around ~3.90, hinting at suboptimal convergence or potential overfitting on train without validation gain. The sweet spot appears around 1e-3 for loss minimization within the three-epoch window.

Overlay of predicted vs ground truth values for a third synthetic sequence run continues to show misalignment in peak magnitudes and positions. Very few matching peaks are observed, and the trajectory remains jittery. This consistent pattern across multiple seeds underscores that hyperparameter changes so far have not significantly improved sequence tracking. More epochs or a curriculum on synthetic sequence complexity may be needed.

Overlay of predicted vs ground truth for a fourth run again exhibits erratic alignment: the model correctly tracks some mid-range values (~20–35) but fails dramatically on large spikes (~45–50) and low troughs (~0–5). Prediction noise persists across runs, suggesting that retention improvements observed in retention ratio plots have not translated into faithful sequence reconstruction.

Memory retention curves for PG19, ArXiv and WikiText show a consistent decrease in training retention ratios over the two epochs, indicating that the EA-ACM module is progressively compressing older context. Validation retention for PG19 and WikiText also mildly decreases, while ArXiv validation increases slightly, suggesting that the entropy-based criterion may be preserving more novel tokens that boost validation performance on ArXiv at this compression rate.

PG19 loss curves indicate a steady decline in both training (4.18 → 3.29) and validation loss (3.60 → 3.27) from epoch 0 to 1. The validation curve closely tracks the training curve, with a small generalization gap maintained, demonstrating effective learning and controlled overfitting under the EA-ACM scheme.

ArXiv loss curves exhibit a larger absolute drop in training loss (8.10 → 4.90) compared to validation loss (5.70 → 5.19). The gap narrows substantially by epoch 1, hinting that compression retains enough high-entropy tokens to support generalization despite the greater inherent difficulty of the ArXiv dataset.

ArXiv memory retention separately plotted confirms a decline in training retention (3.255 → 3.175) and an upward trend on validation retention (3.185 → 3.215). This divergence suggests that the module’s entropy-aware filtering might be better tuned for validation sequences, perhaps capturing salient tokens unseen during training.

WikiText retention ratios decrease modestly in both train (3.328 → 3.308) and val (3.325 → 3.298) over epochs. The parallel trends indicate a balanced compression strategy: high-entropy tokens are kept, but the overall memory budget is strictly enforced, leading to consistent but controlled retention decay.

WikiText loss curves show strong learning dynamics, with training loss dropping from 10.20 → 7.10 and validation from 9.10 → 7.40. The crossing point near epoch 1 (train slightly below val) implies robust generalization with minimal overfitting, reinforcing that EA-ACM’s adaptive compression sustains model capacity on this dataset.

PG19 retention-only curves reaffirm a gentle decay in train (3.105 → 3.063) and val (3.060 → 3.050). The tight alignment between train/val retention suggests the entropy threshold is well calibrated for PG19, preserving a stable set of informative tokens under a fixed memory reduction schedule.

Aggregated loss comparison across PG19, ArXiv and WikiText highlights that all three datasets benefit from EA-ACM: losses decrease every epoch and generalization gaps remain small. The largest absolute gains are on WikiText and ArXiv, reflecting EA-ACM’s utility on long-range and diverse-domain corpora.

Loss curves on all three datasets show a clear decrease in both training and validation losses from epoch 0 to epoch 1. Training loss drops most steeply: pg19 from ~3.45 to ~2.42, scientific_papers_arxiv from ~3.28 to ~2.77, and wikitext_wikitext-2-raw-v1 from ~2.47 to ~1.40. Validation loss also decreases but more modestly: pg19 from ~2.95 to ~2.70, scientific_papers_arxiv from ~2.63 to ~2.54, and wikitext from ~1.50 to ~1.33. This indicates that the model is learning effectively across all domains, with no immediate signs of overfitting in the first two epochs.

The consistent but small drop suggests that as the model compresses more tokens, per-slot informational value is marginally reduced, yet remains high, with wikitext retaining the best efficiency.

Memory retention ratios are stable and slightly increasing over epochs, hovering around 0.77–0.78. pg19 moves from ~0.7715 to ~0.7725 (train) and ~0.773 to ~0.773 (val). scientific_papers_arxiv increases from ~0.777 to ~0.781 (train) and ~0.779 to ~0.785 (val). wikitext_wikitext-2-raw-v1 rises from ~0.7665 to ~0.7679 (train) and ~0.7672 to ~0.7680 (val). Higher retention on scientific_papers_arxiv indicates that more tokens deemed novel (high entropy) are preserved, whereas wikitext sees the lowest retention but remains consistent.

This indicates that the EA-ACM module is able to gradually compress memory without losing much novel information on the validation set, although the training set sees a larger entropy reduction, suggesting effective learning of token importance.
